id ispermalink="false"> /内容/bct0ilvskic1g12rjas7q0a4nstq73uj</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/the-economist-reads/2023/09/01/what-to-read-to-understand-cities </item><item><title><![CDATA[Falling population, rising costs: what is bedevilling the City of Angels?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<section class="css-1ugvd2u e18wk22u0"><style data-emotion="css qts40t">.css-qts40t img{display:block;}.css-qts40t .edweubf2{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-qts40t e1197rjj0"><img alt="洛杉矶市中心前面的天际线上，棕榈树矗立在房屋上方。" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_PDP508.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><p data-caps="initial" class="article__body-text article__body-text--dropcap">天使之城<span data-caps="initial">完美</span><small>的</small>气候和蓬勃发展的经济吸引了一代又一代的加州梦想家。但现在<a href="https://www.economist.com/united-states/2023/08/17/the-hollywood-strikes-reveal-los-angeless-deepest-anxieties">美国第二大城市正在变得越来越小</a>——人口和企业都在流失。正如<a href="https://www.economist.com/podcasts/2023/07/27/why-is-hollywood-on-strike">好莱坞罢工所揭示的</a>那样，住房、生活和经营企业的高昂成本正在将洛杉矶人赶走。这座城市能否扭转大收缩的局面？但洛杉矶变小还有问题吗？</p><p class="article__body-text">该市市长凯伦·巴斯和一名纠察演员阐述了该市面临的负担能力问题，而洛杉矶县经济发展公司的香农·塞奇威克则解释了商业外流背后的原因。我们回顾了这座城市过去的繁荣岁月，加州公共政策研究所的汉斯·约翰逊探讨了如何让它们回归。</p><p class="article__body-text">约翰·普里多 (John Prideaux) 与夏洛特·霍华德 (Charlotte Howard) 和伊德里斯·卡隆 (Idrees Kahloon) 共同主持。</p><p class="article__body-text">时长：45分钟</p><p class="article__body-text"><iframe height="215" src="https://embed.acast.com/checksandbalance/checks-and-balance-los-diablos-de-los-angeles" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></p><p class="article__body-text">现在，您可以<a href="https://www.economist.com/checkspod" data-tegid="d0fgcd8nh46pfpoj91eiou25fqf2uodg">在一个地方</a>找到《制衡》的每一集，并订阅我们的每周时事<a href="https://www.economist.com/newsletters">通讯</a>。如需完全访问印刷版、数字版和音频版以及独家现场活动，请通过<a href="http://economist.com/USpod">coneconomicist.com/uspod</a>订阅<i>《经济学人》</i> 。</p> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 01 Sep 2023 15:48:57 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/66tu3rvn5sc32cr0j3fkgl1fhikni0pd</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/podcasts/2023/09/01/falling-population-rising-costs-what-is-bedevilling-the-city-of-angels </item><item><title><![CDATA[How successful is egg freezing at preserving fertility?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div class="css-11howfu e1h2142t0"><style data-emotion="css qts40t">.css-qts40t img{display:block;}.css-qts40t .edweubf2{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-qts40t e1197rjj0"><img theme="[object Object]" alt="" loading="lazy" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 700px, (min-width: 1280px) 50vw, (min-width: 960px) 66vw, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/img/b/256/144/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 256w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/360/202/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 360w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/384/216/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 384w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/480/270/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 480w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/600/337/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 600w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/834/469/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 834w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/960/540/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 960w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/1096/616/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 1096w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/720/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 1280w, https://www.economist.com/img/b/1424/801/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1424/801/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOT904.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></div><style data-emotion="css kp96v5">.css-kp96v5{font-family:var(--ds-type-system-serif);font-size:var(--ds-type-scale-4);font-weight:normal;line-height:var(--ds-type-leading-upper);}.css-kp96v5 a{-webkit-text-decoration:none;text-decoration:none;color:var(--ds-color-london-5);display:block;}.css-kp96v5 a:hover,.css-kp96v5 a:hover .e1a1xyav0{color:var(--ds-color-chicago-30);-webkit-text-decoration:underline;text-decoration:underline;}.css-kp96v5 a:focus,.css-kp96v5 a:focus .e1a1xyav0{background-color:var(--ds-color-chicago-95);color:var(--ds-color-london-5);outline:none;-webkit-text-decoration:underline;text-decoration:underline;}.css-kp96v5 a:active,.css-kp96v5 a:active .e1a1xyav0{color:var(--ds-color-chicago-30);}.css-kp96v5 a::before{bottom:0;content:'';display:block;left:0;opacity:0;overflow:hidden;position:absolute;right:0;text-indent:-999em;top:0;white-space:nowrap;z-index:1;}.css-kp96v5+.e18dusm60,.css-kp96v5+style+.e18dusm60{margin-top:0.5rem;}.e1p220na0 .css-kp96v5+.e18dusm60{margin-top:0;}</style><h3 class="css-kp96v5 ek2dy8o0"> <a href="https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2023/08/31/wagner-routinely-targets-civilians-in-africa" data-analytics="more_from:headline_1">瓦格纳经常针对非洲平民</a></h3><style data-emotion="css if8akf">.css-if8akf{color:var(--ds-color-london-10);font-family:var(--ds-type-system-serif);max-width:43.75rem;font-size:1.125rem;line-height:var(--ds-type-leading-lower);}.e1frerie0 .css-if8akf{font-size:var(--ds-type-scale-2);}</style><p class="css-if8akf e18dusm60">他们的袭击比国家军队或叛乱分子的袭击更加致命</p><p data-caps="initial" class="article__body-text article__body-text--dropcap"><small>大约十年</small><span data-caps="initial">前</span>，商业卵子冷冻有望让女性更好地控制自己<a href="https://www.economist.com/1843/2022/02/14/tinder-drove-me-to-freeze-my-eggs">不断滴答作响</a>的生物钟。年龄是女性生育能力的决定因素。女性生来就有尽可能多的卵细胞，这些卵细胞会逐渐成熟、耗尽和降解。因此，当冷​​冻技术的进步意味着卵细胞（或“卵母细胞”）可以被冷冻并随后解冻，而对其质量和受精能力影响很小或没有影响时，人们的兴趣就猛增了。突然间，卵母细胞冷冻保存或卵子冷冻似乎成为延长女性生育年龄的可行选择。但这项技术兑现了这一承诺吗？</p><p class="article__body-text">希望保留卵子的女性会经历<a href="https://www.economist.com/technology-quarterly/2023-07-22">体外受精周期</a>的第一阶段（减去受精）。她们每天注射激素，以增加卵巢中能够在一个月经周期内受精的卵子数量。对于 35 岁以下的健康女性来说，这可能意味着 10 到 20 个卵子。使用插入卵巢的针将它们从卵巢中取出，然后脱水并冷冻。在过去的十年中，这一过程越来越多地被使用，不仅出于医疗需要（例如，对于接受化疗的女性），而且也被那些希望在晚年生孩子的女性所使用。为了评估成功率，我们使用迄今为止最大的美国选择性冷冻卵子研究，显示了通过冷冻卵子生育婴儿的机会。 </p><figure class="g-fallback" data-infographic-class="g-fallback"></figure><figure class="interactive-figure"><iframe height="NaN" src="https://infographics.economist.com/2023/20230902_WOC340/" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></figure><p class="article__body-text">纽约大学 ( <small>NYU</small> ) 研究人员进行的这项研究仅对纽约一家生育诊所的 543 名患者进行了观察。但他们的论文之所以引人注目，是因为它跟踪了近二十年的真实临床结果，而大多数其他研究都是基于数学模型。研究人员发现，39% 的女性能够使用她们冷冻的卵子生下至少一个孩子，这可能需要在 15 年期间进行多次尝试。</p><p class="article__body-text">此数据中存在重要警告。由于冷冻卵子在过去十年才成为主流（直到2012年在美国才被认为是“实验性”），尝试使用冷冻卵子的女性数量仍然相对较少。大多数研究也没有区分健康女性的选择性冷冻和出于医疗目的的冷冻，这可能会扭曲结果。至少还需要十年才能对该手术保留生育能力的能力得出更广泛的结论。 </p><div class="adComponent_advert__V79Pp adComponent_incontent__Bxd2J adComponent_hidden___o_ZB advert--inline"><div><div id="econ-1" class="adComponent_adcontainer__dO1Zm"></div></div></div><p class="article__body-text">对于想要更快找到答案的女性来说，目前的数据表明有两个重要因素会影响成功率：冷冻卵子的年龄和储存的卵子数量（并非所有卵子都能在解冻后存活）。<small>纽约大学</small>的研究发现，在 38 岁之前冷冻卵子的女性，至少有 51% 的机会活产，如果她们能够成功解冻至少 20 个卵子，这一数字就会上升到 70%。与此同时，对于 41 岁或以上开始冷冻卵子的女性来说，成功率仅为 23%，如果解冻至少 10 个卵子，则成功率为 33%（卵子数量多于这个年龄组的差异较小）。</p><div class="article__body-text-image"><figure> <span itemscope="" itemprop="image" itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject" data-slim="1"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/1330/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png"><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/1330/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png" srcset="https://www.economist.com/img/b/200/208/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 200w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/300/312/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 300w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/400/416/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 400w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/600/623/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 600w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/640/665/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 640w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/800/831/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 800w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1000/1039/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 1000w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/1330/90/media-assets/image/20230902_WOC378.png 1280w" sizes="336px" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></span></figure><p class="article__body-text">其他研究，包括一项关于西班牙选择性冷冻卵子的研究以及对美国全国数据的分析，也得出了类似的结论。从一方面来看，用冷冻卵子生出孩子的几率并不是特别高。但放在其他背景下，这些机会看起来会更大：英国 2018 年发布的一份报告显示，18 岁时，女性每个月自然受孕的几率为 25%。到了 35 岁，这一比例已降至 10%。但对于冷冻卵子的女性来说，使用卵子的年龄和冷冻卵子的时间长短似乎对她们的成功率没有影响。</p><p class="article__body-text">有人担心，年轻女性对选择性冷冻的部分需求源于这样一种信念：这种做法是万无一失的。但组建家庭从来都不是一件确定的事情。冷冻卵子所带来的好处是，随着年龄的增长，怀有希望的母亲的成功率会降低。那么，这并不是一个万无一失的办法，而是他们未来选择的扩展。■</p><p class="article__body-text"><b>阅读有关此主题的更多信息：</b><br> • <a href="https://www.economist.com/1843/2022/02/14/tinder-drove-me-to-freeze-my-eggs">Tinder 促使我冷冻卵子</a><br>• <a href="https://www.economist.com/technology-quarterly/2023/07/17/some-women-need-eggs-from-others-or-from-their-younger-selves">有些女性需要别人的卵子，或者年轻时的自己的卵子</a><br>•<a href="https://www.economist.com/technology-quarterly/2023-07-22">体外受精：最个性化的技术</a><br>•<a href="https://www.economist.com/leaders/2023/07/20/making-babymaking-better">更好地照顾婴儿</a></p></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 01 Sep 2023 13:05:05 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/aqhqfakdt0t1u6i27s2c8a0ieuftg45r</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2023/09/01/how-successful-is-egg-freezing-at-preserving-fertility </item><item><title><![CDATA[“Influencer boxing” is a welcome distraction]]></title><description><![CDATA[<section class="css-1ugvd2u e18wk22u0"><style data-emotion="css qts40t">.css-qts40t img{display:block;}.css-qts40t .edweubf2{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-qts40t e1197rjj0"><img alt="洛根·保罗和 KSI 互殴" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230902_CUP505.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/con